Psychologists call it “embodied cognition”—the idea that our bodies remember what our minds rush past. A ritual, repeated over time, carves a neural pathway so smooth that it becomes instinct. In crisis, we return to them: the ritual of making the bed, the walk around the block, the list of three things we’re grateful for at bedtime. Not because they solve problems, but because they remind us: *You are still here. You can still begin.*

